StringWithMarkup.String: Bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl sulfide's production and use as a vulcanization accelerator may result in its release to the environment through various waste streams. If released to the atmosphere, bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl) sulfide will exist in both the vapor and particulate phases in the ambient atmosphere based on an estimated vapor pressure of 2.7X10-4 mm Hg at 25 °C. Vapor-phase bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl) sulfide is degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically produced hydroxyl radicals with an estimated half-life of about 3 hours. Particulate-phase bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl) sulfide may be physically removed from the air by wet and dry deposition. An estimated Koc of 10 suggests that bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl) sulfide will have very high mobility in soil. Volatilization from moist soil surfaces may occur because of the moderate Henry's Law constant. Based on data for a similar compound, the disulfide (tetramethylthiuram disulfide), bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl) sulfide is expected to be resistant to aerobic biodegradation in soil and water; over a 4 week period, tetramethylthiuram disulfide (at 100 mg/L, sewage inoculum) reached 2.8% of the theoretical BOD. Bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl) sulfide, as a powdered additive placed onto a membrane or resin support and buried in soil, did not support microbial growth over a 3 month period. Bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl) sulfide will volatilize from water surfaces given an estimated Henry's Law constant of 1.7X10-5 atm-cu m/mole. Estimated half-lives for a model river and model lake are 3 and 28 days, respectively. Bioconcentration in aquatic organisms is unlikely based on an estimated BCF value of 2. Exposure to bis(dimethylthiocarbamoyl) sulfide may occur occupationally during its production or use in the manufacture of other products. (SRC)

Section.Description: Sorption to soils and sediments is an important factor on the transport and fate of organic contaminants in the environment.  The soil/water adsorption coefficient, also known as solid-water distribution coefficient (Kd), measures the amount of chemical substance adsorbed onto soil per amount of water.  Since adsorption occurs predominantly by partition into the soil organic matter, it is more useful to normalize the Kd value to the organic carbon content of a soil and express the distribution coefficient in Koc (organic carbon normalized distribution coefficient).  The greater the Kd (or Koc) value, the less likely a chemical will leach or contribute to runoff.  A very high value means it is strongly adsorbed onto soil and organic matter and does not move throughout the soil.
